    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="324"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d324">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.24 Raw Materials/964</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of the Treasury</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-09">May 9,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Sumner</hi>: Please accept my thanks for your letter
                    of May 8, 1940, concerning arrangements being made to ask Congress immediately
                    to increase appropriations for the building up of reserve stocks of strategic
                    raw materials.</p>
                <p>An estimate of $12,500,000 has been included in the Treasury Deficiency Bill,
                    which will be presented to the Budget in the near future. This estimate will be
                    defended before the Appropriations Committee by the Procurement Division of the
                    Treasury and assistance will be given in such defense by representatives of the
                    Army, who are thoroughly cognizant of the uses to which the raw materials
                    purchased will be put and the reasons for the kinds of material that are
                    acquired.</p>
                <p>With you, I share the hopes that the combined efforts that may be put behind this
                    Deficiency Bill will result in the appropriation by Congress of the funds
                    sought.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">H. Morgenthau, Jr</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
